The Butane Tank Blending is a batch type process based on seasonal RVP adjustments. Butane is received by truck (transports) and piped directly to and injected into the gasoline recirculation line associated with the product tank to be blended. Process safety controls include a skid emergency shutoff valve with multiple, manual actuators and fusible element along with a "Smart-Hose", low emission hose coupler, and thermal/hydrostatic reliefs. Access to the Terminal is restricted to authorized employees, management personnel and authorized contractors/visitors.

B. GENERAL ACCIDENTAL RELEASE PREVENTION PROGRAM AND CHEMICAL-SPECIFIC PREVENTION MEASURES

The Jackson LP Terminal accidental release prevention programs and emergency planning/response programs help effectively manage the hazards posed by the regulated substances to the Terminal employees, surrounding public, and environment. The covered process is regulated by the EPA RMP regulation 40 CFR Part 68, as well as the OSHA Process Safety Management standard 29 CFR 1910.119. The following accident prevention program elements are in place at the Terminal:

1) Employee Participation;
2) Process Safety Information;
3) Process Hazard Analysis (PHA);
4) Standard Operating Procedures;
5) Training;
6) Contractors;
7) Pre-startup Safety Review;
8) Mechanical Integrity with Preventive Maintenance;
9) Hazardous Work Permits/Procedures;
10)Management of Change;
11)Incident or Potential Catastrophic Event Investigation;

12)Emergency Response;
13) Compliance Audits; and
14) Trade Secrets.

These fourteen (14) individual elements of this prevention program work together to prevent accidental chemical releases. MPLX and its employees are committed to the standards required by these management programs. In addition to the training noted above, MPLX also has specific prevention measures that are employed as part of the Terminal's operating procedures and engineering and administrative controls to help identify/contain/control a release, and reduce the consequences of a release. These are briefly summarized as follows:

General Risk Reduction and Safety Measures

-Engineering and construction in accordance with recognized industry and company standards;
-Equipment properly designed with protection from overpressure (pressure safety relief valves, etc.);
-Updated technical drawings, Piping & Instrument Diagrams and Process/Block Flow Diagrams;
-Operating systems monitored and controlled by trained Operators;
-Redundant control systems;
-Manual shutdown devices for critical systems;
-Scheduled inspection and testing of safety devices;
-Limited/secured facility access;
-Regular safety meetings and safety awareness programs;
-Routinely scheduled safety inspections and audits; and
-Frequent unit surveillance by operators.

General Release Mitigation

-Process and remotely operated shut-offs to limit release quantity (also actuated via a fusible element);
-Strategically located valves to isolate leaks; and
-"Smart-Hose" with design break-away and self-closing valves on each end.

General Emergency Response

-Emergency alert system;
-Periodic emergency training for employees;
-Communication systems with local emergency responders and regulatory agencies; and
-Emergency drills with Terminal personnel, regulatory agencies, and community emergency responders to enhance response skills and coordination among agencies.

